Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission for Computing and Freedoms has authorised 774 fingerprint recognition systems, hand shape or hand vein network in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime,” Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology in Washington, D.C., said in a statement.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new technologies, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contour and venous network of the palm or finger.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
“For example, some people who work on concrete have very bad fingerprints and their fingerprints are illegible,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand implies a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - one cannot capture this data unknowingly - and a drawback: sometimes the procedure has to be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
By increasing the precision of the sensors and the computational capacity of the computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the last five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and the Netherlands have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but a silent environment is needed,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infalsible marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
“In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data,” confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, CNIL’s research, innovation and prospects director.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers law enforcement services a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>90,000 suitcase to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing a person among others) and authentication (ensure that the person is who he claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issuance of identity papers: the biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information the state has on all citizens already filed.
This ensures that a person does not try to overwhelm someone else’s identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
“We retrieve the images from surveillance cameras and compare them with the photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, NEC France’s commercial development officer for biometric identification solutions.
Another use: take a photo of a quidam who makes the tail in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (frontiers, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control has been added.
“A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the friend pointing for another,” explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing its card and placing its hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and in Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and signs of large distribution: at the time of paying in the store with his bank card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a scanner that scans the veins.
The experiment is expected to last for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
“If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash for thirty seconds less, it’s appreciative,” explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: within a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailored options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Digital fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure case, which is blocked if you try to move it,” says Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy specialists, they, continue to be concerned.
“The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, scare me the worst: widespread surveillance,” predicts Andrew Patrick, of the Canadian Privacy Commissioner.
