Scientists have just highlighted how a dog’s tail movements are related to his mood.
Previous studies have revealed that happy dogs move their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs move it more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that, in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what it was like in other species.
He added that just as in humans, the right side of the brain in dogs was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers followed animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will certainly not take long for us to understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented to dogs movies that featured other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion – and we were able to traffic the tail movement and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog without expression swinging the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog swinging the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a tail turning mainly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view that pushes the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other thanks to these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added, “If you meet other dogs several times and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail toward one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on this experience.”
The researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine Behavior Expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol’s School of Veterinary Sciences, said it was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, “Dogs would go more easily to a robot dog when his tail swinged to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious – the opposite of what is stated in the Italian study.”
He pointed out that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the different studies did not fully consider movie animals or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“While many elements, detected in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
