A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society of New York has identified a new species of dolphin on the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Mission Officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Marine Environments (OCEAMM) returns for L’Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of dolphin?
It’s good news, but I’m not particularly surprised.
While species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographic basis in the past, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in species classification sciences.
Moreover, it is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to question the classification or affiliation of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged due to advances in genetics.
In the same way, two very close species have been distinguished morphologically thanks to genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About a decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific squid dolphins and Atlantic squid whales.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery, as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of massive mortality caused by a viral outbreak or accidental catch occurs in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than the local extinction of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered to be endangered or in danger of extinction depending on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the new species discovered has emerged, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
The marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there is many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Marianne Cave, just 11 kilometres from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money on the search for life on other planets than on marine research, and it’s time for that to change.
