For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and go to hospitals that were not equipped to come to his aid.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma from which he would carry the sequels for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him overseas if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he could get any treatment he could benefit from.
“It’s not easy,” adds Mr. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., go to the hospital to be the first, and you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwell's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two in five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country’s health expenditures are in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” Dr. Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have performed more than 700 surgical acts for free over the past year.
He became a physician himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas over the weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they land in vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and crossing hard terrain to get to the villages that need the most help.
Luck doesn’t always follow them.
They had to push vehicles many times to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best housing available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle – with his big smile and overwhelming energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people on each visit,” said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment against malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive bouquets, a pair of glasses collected or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the practice team of simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, town hall, or home; after the intervention, the patient rises and goes to the wake-up room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the electrogen group, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It’s an exciting pace, but the musicians in the villages generally help the team stay motivated.
“They hit drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returns to the city, tired but proud of the work it has done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgical acts for free over the past year, and he knows that their presence can make all the difference for those they come to help.
A man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
“This will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to living this traveling hospital and working as a surgeon in the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, that finances 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in the Dr. Bwelle group.
He is still in the hospital or is trying to find money for his association in order to run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, it's an opportunity to learn on the field that they don't have at home.
“We were able to participate in operations to help sponge the blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley said.
It’s not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you’re studying medicine in your second year.
Volunteer students generally pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transportation and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
“It’s a hero, there’s no doubt,” said Katie O’Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not nearly extinct.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” added Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and alleviating pain are the reasons that motivate me to do this.
